# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: parasitic-oscillation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] An **audio power amplifier** (or **power amp**) amplifies low-power electronic audio signals, such as the signal from a radio receiver or an electric guitar pickup, to a level that is high enough for driving loudspeakers or headphones.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Audio power amplifiers are found in all manner of sound systems, including sound reinforcement, public address, home audio systems and musical instrument amplifiers like guitar amplifiers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] It is the final electronic stage in a typical audio playback chain before the signal is sent to the loudspeakers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The preceding stages in such a chain are low-power audio amplifiers, which perform tasks like pre-amplification of the signal, equalization, mixing different input signals.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The inputs can also be any number of audio sources like record players, CD players, digital audio players and cassette players.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Most audio power amplifiers require these low-level inputs, which are line level.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The audio amplifier was invented around 1912 by Lee de Forest.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] This was made possible by his invention of the first practical amplifying electrical component, the triode vacuum tube (or "valve" in British English) in 1907.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The triode was a three-terminal device with a control grid that can modulate the flow of electrons from the filament to the plate.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The triode vacuum amplifier was used to make the first AM radio.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Early audio power amplifiers were based on vacuum tubes and some of these achieved notably high audio quality (e.g., the Williamson amplifier of 1947–9).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Audio power amplifiers based on transistors became practical with the wide availability of inexpensive transistors in the late 1960s.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Since the 1970s, most modern audio amplifiers are based on solid-state transistors, especially the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) and the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Transistor-based amplifiers are lighter in weight, more reliable and require less maintenance than tube amplifiers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960. was adapted into a power MOSFET for audio by Jun-ichi Nishizawa at Tohoku University in 1974.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Power MOSFETs were soon manufactured by Yamaha for their hi-fi audio amplifiers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] JVC, Pioneer Corporation, Sony and Toshiba also began manufacturing amplifiers with power MOSFETs in 1974.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] In 1977, Hitachi introduced the LDMOS (lateral diffused MOS), a type of power MOSFET.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Hitachi was the only LDMOS manufacturer between 1977 and 1983, during which time LDMOS was used in audio power amplifiers from manufacturers such as HH Electronics (V-series) and Ashly Audio, and were used for music and public address systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Class-D amplifiers became successful in the mid-1980s when low-cost, fast-switching MOSFETs were made available.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Many transistor amps use MOSFET devices in their power sections, because their distortion curve is more tube-like.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Key design parameters for audio power amplifiers are frequency response, gain, noise, and distortion.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] These are interdependent; increasing gain often leads to undesirable increases in noise and distortion.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] While negative feedback actually reduces the gain, it also reduces distortion.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Most audio amplifiers are linear amplifiers operating in class AB.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Until the 1970s, most amplifiers used vacuum tubes.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] During the 1970s, tube amps were increasingly replaced with transistor-based amplifiers, which were lighter in weight, more reliable, and lower maintenance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The class-D amplifier, which is much more efficient than class-AB amplifiers, is now widely used in consumer electronics audio products, bass amplifiers and sound reinforcement system gear, as class-D amplifiers are much lighter in weight and produce much less heat, but may introduce some noise.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Since modern digital devices, including CD and DVD players, radio receivers and tape decks already provide a "flat" signal at line level, the preamp is not needed other than as a volume control and source selector.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] One alternative to a separate preamp is to simply use passive volume and switching controls, sometimes integrated into a power amplifier to form an integrated amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The final stage of amplification, after preamplifiers, is the output stage, where the highest demands are placed on the transistors or tubes.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] For this reason, the design choices made around the output device (for single-ended output stages, such as in single-ended triode amplifiers) or devices (for push-pull output stages), such as the class of operation of the output devices is often taken as the description of the whole power amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] For example, a class-B amplifier will probably have just the high power output devices operating cut off for half of each cycle, while the other devices (such as differential amplifier, voltage amplifier and possibly even driver transistors) operate in class A.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] In a transformerless output stage, the devices are essentially in series with the power supply and output load (such as a loudspeaker), possibly via some large capacitor and/or small resistances.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] For some years following the introduction of solid-state amplifiers, their *perceived* sound did not have the excellent audio quality of the best valve audio amplifiers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] This led audiophiles to believe that tube sound had an intrinsic quality due to the vacuum tube technology itself.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] In 1970, Matti Otala published a paper on transient distortion.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Transient distortion later became known as transient intermodulation distortion (TIM).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Two years later, in a 1972 paper, Matti Otala reported that TIM was found to occur during very rapid increases in amplifier output voltage.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Papers also later revealed that TIM distortion was triggered not just by transients, but also by steady state sine tone measurements.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Further publications by Otala and other authors found the solution for TIM distortion, including increasing slew rate, decreasing preamp frequency bandwidth, and the insertion of a lag compensation circuit in the input stage of the amplifier in a way that makes the input stage more linear.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The next step in advanced design was the Baxandall Theorem, created by Peter Baxandall in England.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] This theorem introduced the concept of comparing the ratio between the input distortion and the output distortion of an amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] This new idea helped audio design engineers to better evaluate the distortion processes within an amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] By applying negative feedback, the Baxandall Effect can come into play, where, as the level of negative feedback is increased over a limited range, the 2nd harmonic distortion product is reduced as expected, but at the same time, the higher-order harmonic distortion products are increased instead.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] This has led to the myth that high levels of negative feedback are bad.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] However, as the level of negative feedback is increased beyond approximately 20 dB, all distortion products are further reduced, demonstrating that such higher levels of negative feedback have no downsides.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Important applications include public address systems, theatrical and concert sound reinforcement systems, and domestic systems such as a stereo or home-theatre system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Instrument amplifiers including guitar amplifiers and electric keyboard amplifiers also use audio power amplifiers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] In some cases, the power amplifier for an instrument amplifier is integrated into a single amplifier "head" which contains a preamplifier, tone controls, and electronic effects.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] These components may be mounted in a wooden speaker cabinet to create a "combo amplifier".
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Musicians with unique performance needs and/or a need for very powerful amplification may create a custom setup with separate rackmount preamplifiers, equalizers, and a power amplifier mounted in a 19" road case.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Power amplifiers are available in standalone units, which are used by hi-fi audio enthusiasts and designers of public address systems (PA systems) and sound reinforcement systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] A hi-fi user of power amplifiers may have a stereo power amplifier to drive left and right speakers and a single-channel (mono) power amplifier to drive a subwoofer.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] The number of power amplifiers used in a sound reinforcement setting depends on the size of the venue.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] A small coffeehouse may have a single power amp driving two PA speakers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] A nightclub may have several power amps for the main speakers, one or more power amps for the monitor speakers (pointing towards the band) and an additional power amp for the subwoofer.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] A stadium concert may have a large number of power amps mounted in racks.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-amplifier] Most consumer electronics sound products, such as TVs, boom boxes, home cinema sound systems, Casio and Yamaha electronic keyboards, "combo" guitar amps and car stereos have power amplifiers integrated inside the chassis of the main product.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Feedback is almost always considered undesirable when it occurs with a singer's or public speaker's microphone at an event using a sound reinforcement system or PA system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Since the 1960s, electric guitar players in rock music bands using loud guitar amplifiers, speaker cabinets and distortion effects have intentionally created guitar feedback to create different sounds including long sustained tones that cannot be produced using standard playing techniques.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The sound of guitar feedback is considered to be a desirable musical effect in heavy metal music, hardcore punk and grunge.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Jimi Hendrix was an innovator in the intentional use of guitar feedback in his guitar solos to create unique musical sounds.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] If the small-signal gain is greater than 1 for some frequency, then the system will start to oscillate at that frequency because noise at that frequency will be amplified.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Sound will be produced without anyone actually playing.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The sound level will increase until the output starts clipping, reducing the loop gain to exactly unity.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] This is the principle upon which electronic oscillators are based; in that case, although the feedback loop is purely electronic, the principle is the same.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] If the gain is large but slightly less than 1, then ringing will be introduced, but only when at least some input sound is already being sent through the system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Early academic work on acoustical feedback was done by Dr.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Boner was responsible for establishing basic theories of acoustic feedback, room-ring modes, and room-sound system equalizing techniques.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Boner reasoned that when feedback happened, it did so at one precise frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] He also reasoned that it could be stopped by inserting a very narrow notch filter at that frequency in the loudspeaker's signal chain.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] He worked with Gifford White, founder of White Instruments to hand craft notch filters for specific feedback frequencies in specific rooms.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] To maximize gain before feedback, the amount of sound energy that is fed back to the microphones must be reduced as much as is practical.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] As sound pressure falls off with 1/r with respect to the distance r in free space, or up to a distance known as reverberation distance in closed spaces (and the energy density with 1/r2), it is important to keep the microphones at a large enough distance from the speaker systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] As well, microphones should not be positioned in front of speakers, and individuals using mics should be asked to avoid pointing the microphone at speaker enclosures.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Additionally, the loudspeakers and microphones should have non-uniform directivity and should stay out of the maximum sensitivity of each other, ideally in a direction of cancellation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Public address speakers often achieve directivity in the mid and treble region (and good efficiency) via horn systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Sometimes the woofers have a cardioid characteristic.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] This configuration reduces the opportunities for feedback and allows independent control of the sound pressure levels for the audience and the performers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Almost always, the natural frequency response of a sound reinforcement systems is not ideally flat as this leads to acoustical feedback at the frequency with the highest loop gain, which may be a resonance with much higher than the average gain over all frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] It is therefore helpful to apply some form of equalization to reduce the gain at this frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Feedback can be reduced manually by ringing out a sound system prior to a performance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The sound engineer can increase the level of a microphone until feedback occurs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The engineer can then attenuate the relevant frequency on an equalizer, preventing feedback at that frequency but allowing sufficient volume at other frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Many professional sound engineers can identify feedback frequencies by ear but others use a real-time analyzer to identify the ringing frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] To avoid feedback, an automatic feedback suppressor can be used.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Some of these work by shifting the frequency slightly, with this upshift resulting in a *chirp*-sound instead of a howling sound of unaddressed feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Other devices use sharp notch filters to filter out offending frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Adaptive algorithms are often used to automatically tune these notch filters.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] To intentionally create feedback, an electric guitar player needs a guitar amplifier with very high gain (amplification) or the guitar brought near the speaker.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The guitarist then allows the strings to vibrate freely and brings the guitar close to the loudspeaker of the guitar amp.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The use of distortion effects units adds additional gain and facilitates the creation of intentional feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] A deliberate use of acoustic feedback was pioneered by blues and rock and roll guitarists such as Willie Johnson, Johnny Watson and Link Wray.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] According to AllMusic's Richie Unterberger, the very first use of feedback on a commercial rock record is the introduction of the song "I Feel Fine" by the Beatles, recorded in 1964.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Jay Hodgson agrees that this feedback created by John Lennon leaning a semi-acoustic guitar against an amplifier was the first chart-topper to showcase feedback distortion.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The Who's 1965 hits "Anyway, Anyhow, Anywhere" and "My Generation" featured feedback manipulation by Pete Townshend, with an extended solo in the former and the shaking of his guitar in front of the amplifier to create a throbbing noise in the latter.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Canned Heat's "Fried Hockey Boogie" also featured guitar feedback produced by Henry Vestine during his solo to create a highly amplified, distorted boogie style of feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] In 1963, the teenage Brian May and his father custom-built his signature guitar Red Special, which was purposely designed to feed back.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Feedback was used extensively after 1965 by the Monks, Jefferson Airplane, the Velvet Underground and the Grateful Dead, who included in many of their live shows a segment named *Feedback*, a several-minute-long feedback-driven improvisation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Feedback has since become a striking characteristic of rock music, as electric guitar players such as Jeff Beck, Pete Townshend, Dave Davies, Steve Marriott and Jimi Hendrix deliberately induced feedback by holding their guitars close to the amplifier's speaker.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] An example of feedback can be heard on Hendrix's performance of "Can You See Me?" at the Monterey Pop Festival.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The entire guitar solo was created using amplifier feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Jazz guitarist Gábor Szabó was one of the earliest jazz musicians to use controlled feedback in his music, which is prominent on his live album *The Sorcerer* (1967).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Szabó's method included the use of a flat-top acoustic guitar with a magnetic pickup.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Lou Reed created his album *Metal Machine Music* (1975) entirely from loops of feedback played at various speeds.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Examples of feedback combined with a quick volume swell used as a transition include Weezer's "My Name Is Jonas" and "Say It Ain't So"; The Strokes' "Reptilia", "New York City Cops", and "Juicebox"; Dream Theater's "As I Am"; as well as numerous tracks by Meshuggah and Tool.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Cacophonous feedback fade-outs ending a song are most often used to generate rather than relieve tension, often cross-faded too after a thematic and musical release.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Examples include Modwheelmood's remix of Nine Inch Nail's "The Great Destroyer"; and the Jesus and Mary Chain's "Teenage Lust", "Tumbledown", "Catchfire", "Sundown", and "Frequency".
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Karlheinz Stockhausen in *Solo* (1965-1966) used a single instrument (cello, trombone, etc.), with feedback and electronic music.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Steve Reich makes extensive use of audio feedback in his work *Pendulum Music* (1968) by swinging a series of microphones back and forth in front of their corresponding amplifiers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Hugh Davies and Alvin Lucier both use feedback in their works.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Roland Kayn based much of his compositional oeuvre, which he termed "cybernetic music," on audio systems incorporating feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Pitched melodies may be created entirely from feedback by changing the angle between a guitar and amplifier after establishing a feedback loop.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Examples include Tool's "Jambi", Robert Fripp's guitar on David Bowie's "Heroes" (album version), and Jimi Hendrix's "Third Stone from the Sun" and his live performance of "Wild Thing" at the Monterey Pop Festival.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Audio feedback became a signature feature of many underground rock bands during the 1980s.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] American noise-rockers Sonic Youth melded the rock-feedback tradition with a compositional and classical approach (notably covering Reich's "Pendulum Music"), and guitarist/producer Steve Albini's group Big Black also worked controlled feedback into the makeup of their songs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] With the alternative rock movement of the 1990s, feedback again saw a surge in popular usage by suddenly mainstream acts like Nirvana, the Red Hot Chili Peppers, Rage Against the Machine and the Smashing Pumpkins.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The use of the "no-input-mixer" method for sound generation by feeding a mixing console back into itself has been adopted in experimental electronic and noise music by practitioners such as Toshimaru Nakamura.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The principle of feedback is used in many guitar sustain devices.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Examples include handheld devices like the EBow, built-in guitar pickups that increase the instrument's sonic sustain, and sonic transducers mounted on the head of a guitar.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] Intended closed-circuit feedback can also be created by an effects unit, such as a delay pedal or effect fed back into a mixing console.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The feedback can be controlled by using the fader to determine a volume level.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The Boss DF-2 Super Feedbacker and Distortion pedal is an electronic effect unit that helps electric guitarists create feedback effects.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/audio-feedback] The halldorophone is an electro-acoustic string instrument specifically made to work with string-based feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] In electronics, the **Barkhausen stability criterion** is a mathematical condition to determine when a linear electronic circuit will oscillate.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] It was put forth in 1921 by German physicist Heinrich Barkhausen (1881–1956).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] It is widely used in the design of electronic oscillators, and also in the design of general negative feedback circuits such as op amps, to prevent them from oscillating.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] Barkhausen's criterion applies to linear circuits with a feedback loop.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] It cannot be applied directly to active elements with negative resistance like tunnel diode oscillators.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] The kernel of the criterion is that a complex pole pair must be placed on the imaginary axis of the complex frequency plane if steady state oscillations should take place.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] In the real world, it is impossible to balance on the imaginary axis; small errors will cause the poles to be either slightly to the right or left, resulting in infinite growth or decreasing to zero, respectively.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] Thus, in practice a steady-state oscillator is a non-linear circuit; the poles are manipulated to be slightly to the right, and a nonlinearity is introduced that reduces the loop gain when the output is high.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] Barkhausen's criterion is a *necessary* condition for oscillation but not a *sufficient* condition: some circuits satisfy the criterion but do not oscillate.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] Similarly, the Nyquist stability criterion also indicates instability but is silent about oscillation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] Apparently there is not a compact formulation of an oscillation criterion that is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] Barkhausen's original "formula for self-excitation", intended for determining the oscillation frequencies of the feedback loop, involved an equality sign: |β*A*| = 1.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] At the time conditionally-stable nonlinear systems were poorly understood; it was widely believed that this gave the boundary between stability (|β*A*| < 1) and instability (|β*A*| ≥ 1), and this erroneous version found its way into the literature.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/barkhausen-stability-criterion] However, *sustained* oscillations only occur at frequencies for which equality holds.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In electrical engineering and control theory, a **Bode plot** is a graph of the frequency response of a system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] It is usually a combination of a **Bode magnitude plot**, expressing the magnitude (usually in decibels) of the frequency response, and a **Bode phase plot**, expressing the phase shift.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] As originally conceived by Hendrik Wade Bode in the 1930s, the plot is an asymptotic approximation of the frequency response, using straight line segments.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Among his several important contributions to circuit theory and control theory, engineer Hendrik Wade Bode, while working at Bell Labs in the 1930s, devised a simple but accurate method for graphing gain and phase-shift plots.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] These bear his name, *Bode gain plot* and *Bode phase plot*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] "Bode" is often pronounced in English as /ˈboʊdi/ *BOH-dee*, whereas in Dutch it is usually [ˈboːdə], closer to English /ˈboʊdə/ *BOH-də*, which is preferred by his family, but less common among researchers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Bode was faced with the problem of designing stable amplifiers with feedback for use in telephone networks.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] He developed the graphical design technique of the Bode plots to show the gain margin and phase margin required to maintain stability under variations in circuit characteristics caused during manufacture or during operation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The principles developed were applied to design problems of servomechanisms and other feedback control systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode plot is an example of analysis in the frequency domain.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode plot for a linear, time-invariant system with transfer function $H(s)$ ( s being the complex frequency in the Laplace domain) consists of a magnitude plot and a phase plot.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The **Bode magnitude plot** is the graph of the function $|H(s=j\omega )|$ of frequency $\omega$ (with j being the imaginary unit).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The $\omega$ -axis of the magnitude plot is logarithmic and the magnitude is given in decibels, i.e., a value for the magnitude $|H|$ is plotted on the axis at $20\log _{10}|H|$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The **Bode phase plot** is the graph of the phase, commonly expressed in degrees, of the argument function $\arg \left(H(s=j\omega )\right)$ as a function of $\omega$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The phase is plotted on the same logarithmic $\omega$ -axis as the magnitude plot, but the value for the phase is plotted on a linear vertical axis.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This section illustrates that a Bode plot is a visualization of the frequency response of a system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Consider a linear, time-invariant system with transfer function $H(s)$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] that is applied persistently, i.e. from a time $-\infty$ to a time t .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] i.e., also a sinusoidal signal with amplitude $y_{0}$ shifted by a phase $\varphi$ with respect to the input.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In summary, subjected to an input with frequency $\omega$ , the system responds at the same frequency with an output that is amplified by a factor $|H(\mathrm {j} \omega )|$ and phase-shifted by $\arg H(\mathrm {j} \omega )$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] These quantities, thus, characterize the frequency response and are shown in the Bode plot.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] For many practical problems, the detailed Bode plots can be approximated with straight-line segments that are asymptotes of the precise response.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The effect of each of the terms of a multiple element transfer function can be approximated by a set of straight lines on a Bode plot.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This allows a graphical solution of the overall frequency response function.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Before widespread availability of digital computers, graphical methods were extensively used to reduce the need for tedious calculation; a graphical solution could be used to identify feasible ranges of parameters for a new design.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This idea is used explicitly in the method for drawing phase diagrams.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The method for drawing amplitude plots implicitly uses this idea, but since the log of the amplitude of each pole or zero always starts at zero and only has one asymptote change (the straight lines), the method can be simplified.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Amplitude decibels is usually done using ${\text{dB}}=20\log _{10}(X)$ to define decibels.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] To handle irreducible 2nd-order polynomials, $ax^{2}+bx+c$ can, in many cases, be approximated as $({\sqrt {a}}x+{\sqrt {c}})^{2}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Note that zeros and poles happen when $\omega$ is *equal to* a certain $x_{n}$ or $y_{n}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This is because the function in question is the magnitude of $H(\mathrm {j} \omega )$ , and since it is a complex function, $|H(\mathrm {j} \omega )|={\sqrt {H\cdot H^{*}}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Thus at any place where there is a zero or pole involving the term $(s+x_{n})$ , the magnitude of that term is ${\sqrt {(x_{n}+\mathrm {j} \omega )(x_{n}-\mathrm {j} \omega )}}={\sqrt {x_{n}^{2}+\omega ^{2}}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Note that this correction method does not incorporate how to handle complex values of $x_{n}$ or $y_{n}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In the case of an irreducible polynomial, the best way to correct the plot is to actually calculate the magnitude of the transfer function at the pole or zero corresponding to the irreducible polynomial, and put that dot over or under the line at that pole or zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] the idea is to draw separate plots for each pole and zero, then add them up.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode plot is shown in Figure 1(b) above, and construction of the straight-line approximation is discussed next.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] These two lines meet at the corner frequency $\omega _{\text{c}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] From the plot, it can be seen that for frequencies well below the corner frequency, the circuit has an attenuation of 0 dB, corresponding to a unity pass-band gain, i.e. the amplitude of the filter output equals the amplitude of the input.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Frequencies above the corner frequency are attenuated – the higher the frequency, the higher the attenuation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] versus $\omega$ , where $\omega$ and $\omega _{\text{c}}$ are the input and cutoff angular frequencies respectively.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] For input frequencies much lower than corner, the ratio $\omega /\omega _{\text{c}}$ is small, and therefore the phase angle is close to zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] As the ratio increases, the absolute value of the phase increases and becomes −45° when $\omega =\omega _{\text{c}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] As the ratio increases for input frequencies much greater than the corner frequency, the phase angle asymptotically approaches −90°.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The frequency scale for the phase plot is logarithmic.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The horizontal frequency axis, in both the magnitude and phase plots, can be replaced by the normalized (nondimensional) frequency ratio $\omega /\omega _{\text{c}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In such a case the plot is said to be normalized, and units of the frequencies are no longer used, since all input frequencies are now expressed as multiples of the cutoff frequency $\omega _{\text{c}}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Figures 2–5 further illustrate construction of Bode plots.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This example with both a pole and a zero shows how to use superposition.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] To begin, the components are presented separately.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Figure 2 shows the Bode magnitude plot for a zero and a low-pass pole, and compares the two with the Bode straight line plots.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The straight-line plots are horizontal up to the pole (zero) location and then drop (rise) at 20 dB/decade.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The second Figure 3 does the same for the phase.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The phase plots are horizontal up to a frequency factor of ten below the pole (zero) location and then drop (rise) at 45°/decade until the frequency is ten times higher than the pole (zero) location.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The plots then are again horizontal at higher frequencies at a final, total phase change of 90°.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Figure 4 and Figure 5 show how superposition (simple addition) of a pole and zero plot is done.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode straight line plots again are compared with the exact plots.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The zero has been moved to higher frequency than the pole to make a more interesting example.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Notice in Figure 4 that the 20 dB/decade drop of the pole is arrested by the 20 dB/decade rise of the zero resulting in a horizontal magnitude plot for frequencies above the zero location.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Notice in Figure 5 in the phase plot that the straight-line approximation is pretty approximate in the region where both pole and zero affect the phase.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Notice also in Figure 5 that the range of frequencies where the phase changes in the straight line plot is limited to frequencies a factor of ten above and below the pole (zero) location.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Where the phase of the pole and the zero both are present, the straight-line phase plot is horizontal because the 45°/decade drop of the pole is arrested by the overlapping 45°/decade rise of the zero in the limited range of frequencies where both are active contributors to the phase.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Bode plots are used to assess the stability of negative-feedback amplifiers by finding the gain and phase margins of an amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] where *A*FB is the gain of the amplifier with feedback (the *closed-loop gain*), *β* is the *feedback factor*, and *A*OL is the gain without feedback (the *open-loop gain*).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The gain *A*OL is a complex function of frequency, with both magnitude and phase.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Examination of this relation shows the possibility of infinite gain (interpreted as instability) if the product β*A*OL = −1 (that is, the magnitude of β*A*OL is unity and its phase is −180°, the so-called Barkhausen stability criterion).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Bode plots are used to determine just how close an amplifier comes to satisfying this condition.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Key to this determination are two frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The first, labeled here as *f*180, is the frequency where the open-loop gain flips sign.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The second, labeled here *f*0 dB, is the frequency where the magnitude of the product |β*A*OL| = 1 = 0 dB.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] One measure of proximity to instability is the **gain margin**.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode phase plot locates the frequency where the phase of β*A*OL reaches −180°, denoted here as frequency *f*180.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Using this frequency, the Bode magnitude plot finds the magnitude of β*A*OL.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] If |β*A*OL|180 ≥ 1, the amplifier is unstable, as mentioned.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] If |β*A*OL|180 < 1, instability does not occur, and the separation in dB of the magnitude of |β*A*OL|180 from |β*A*OL| = 1 is called the *gain margin*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Another equivalent measure of proximity to instability is the *phase margin*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode magnitude plot locates the frequency where the magnitude of |β*A*OL| reaches unity, denoted here as frequency *f*0 dB.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Using this frequency, the Bode phase plot finds the phase of β*A*OL.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] If the phase of β*A*OL(*f*0 dB) > −180°, the instability condition cannot be met at any frequency (because its magnitude is going to be < 1 when *f* = *f*180), and the distance of the phase at *f*0 dB in degrees above −180° is called the *phase margin*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] If a simple *yes* or *no* on the stability issue is all that is needed, the amplifier is stable if *f*0 dB < *f*180.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This criterion is sufficient to predict stability only for amplifiers satisfying some restrictions on their pole and zero positions (minimum phase systems).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Although these restrictions usually are met, if they are not, then another method must be used, such as the Nyquist plot.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Optimal gain and phase margins may be computed using Nevanlinna–Pick interpolation theory.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Figures 6 and 7 illustrate the gain behavior and terminology.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] For a three-pole amplifier, Figure 6 compares the Bode plot for the gain without feedback (the *open-loop* gain) *A*OL with the gain with feedback *A*FB (the *closed-loop* gain).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] See negative feedback amplifier for more detail.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In this example, *A*OL = 100 dB at low frequencies, and 1 / β = 58 dB.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] At low frequencies, *A*FB ≈ 58 dB as well.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Because the open-loop gain *A*OL is plotted and not the product β *A*OL, the condition *A*OL = 1 / β decides *f*0 dB.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The feedback gain at low frequencies and for large *A*OL is *A*FB ≈ 1 / β (look at the formula for the feedback gain at the beginning of this section for the case of large gain *A*OL), so an equivalent way to find *f*0 dB is to look where the feedback gain intersects the open-loop gain.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Near this crossover of the two gains at *f*0 dB, the Barkhausen criteria are almost satisfied in this example, and the feedback amplifier exhibits a massive peak in gain (it would be infinity if β *A*OL = −1).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Beyond the unity gain frequency *f*0 dB, the open-loop gain is sufficiently small that *A*FB ≈ *A*OL (examine the formula at the beginning of this section for the case of small *A*OL).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Figure 7 shows the corresponding phase comparison: the phase of the feedback amplifier is nearly zero out to the frequency *f*180 where the open-loop gain has a phase of −180°.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In this vicinity, the phase of the feedback amplifier plunges abruptly downward to become almost the same as the phase of the open-loop amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Comparing the labeled points in Figure 6 and Figure 7, it is seen that the unity gain frequency *f*0 dB and the phase-flip frequency *f*180 are very nearly equal in this amplifier, *f*180 ≈ *f*0 dB ≈ 3.332 kHz, which means the gain margin and phase margin are nearly zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Figures 8 and 9 illustrate the gain margin and phase margin for a different amount of feedback β.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The feedback factor is chosen smaller than in Figure 6 or 7, moving the condition | β *A*OL | = 1 to lower frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] In this example, 1 / β = 77 dB, and at low frequencies *A*FB ≈ 77 dB as well.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] From Figure 8, the intersection of 1 / β and *A*OL occurs at *f*0 dB = 1 kHz.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Notice that the peak in the gain *A*FB near *f*0 dB is almost gone.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Using the value of *f*0 dB = 1 kHz found above from the magnitude plot of Figure 8, the open-loop phase at *f*0 dB is −135°, which is a phase margin of 45° above −180°.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Using Figure 9, for a phase of −180° the value of *f*180 = 3.332 kHz (the same result as found earlier, of course).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The open-loop gain from Figure 8 at *f*180 is 58 dB, and 1 / β = 77 dB, so the gain margin is 19 dB.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Stability is not the sole criterion for amplifier response, and in many applications a more stringent demand than stability is good step response.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] As a rule of thumb, good step response requires a phase margin of at least 45°, and often a margin of over 70° is advocated, particularly where component variation due to manufacturing tolerances is an issue.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] See also the discussion of phase margin in the step response article.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Bode plotter is an electronic instrument resembling an oscilloscope, which produces a Bode diagram, or a graph, of a circuit's voltage gain or phase shift plotted against frequency in a feedback control system or a filter.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] An example of this is shown in Figure 10.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] It is extremely useful for analyzing and testing filters and the stability of feedback control systems, through the measurement of corner (cutoff) frequencies and gain and phase margins.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] This is identical to the function performed by a vector network analyzer, but the network analyzer is typically used at much higher frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] For education and research purposes, plotting Bode diagrams for given transfer functions facilitates better understanding and getting faster results (see external links).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] Two related plots that display the same data in different coordinate systems are the Nyquist plot and the Nichols plot.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] These are parametric plots, with frequency as the input and magnitude and phase of the frequency response as the output.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Nyquist plot displays these in polar coordinates, with magnitude mapping to radius and phase to argument (angle).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/bode-plot] The Nichols plot displays these in rectangular coordinates, on the log scale.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The capacitance between two conductors depends on the opposing surface area of the conductors, the distance between those conductors, and the permittivity of any dielectric material between them.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] For many dielectric materials, the permittivity, and thus the capacitance, is independent of the potential difference between the conductors and the total charge on them.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The SI unit of capacitance is the farad (symbol: F), named after the English physicist Michael Faraday.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] A 1 farad capacitor, when charged with 1 coulomb of electrical charge, has a potential difference of 1 volt between its plates.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The reciprocal of capacitance is called elastance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In discussing electrical circuits, the term *capacitance* is usually a shorthand for the mutual capacitance between two adjacent conductors, such as the two plates of a capacitor.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] However, every isolated conductor also exhibits capacitance, here called *self-capacitance*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] It is measured by the amount of electric charge that must be added to an isolated conductor to raise its electric potential by one unit of measurement, e.g., one volt.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The reference point for this potential is a theoretical hollow conducting sphere, of infinite radius, with the conductor centered inside this sphere.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The inter-winding capacitance of a coil is sometimes called self-capacitance, but this is a different phenomenon.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] It is actually mutual capacitance between the individual turns of the coil and is a form of stray or parasitic capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] This self-capacitance is an important consideration at high frequencies: it changes the impedance of the coil and gives rise to parallel resonance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In many applications this is an undesirable effect and sets an upper frequency limit for the correct operation of the circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] A common form is a parallel-plate capacitor, which consists of two conductive plates insulated from each other, usually sandwiching a dielectric material.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In a parallel plate capacitor, capacitance is very nearly proportional to the surface area of the conductor plates and inversely proportional to the separation distance between the plates.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The discussion above is limited to the case of two conducting plates, although of arbitrary size and shape.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The definition $C=Q/V$ does not apply when there are more than two charged plates, or when the net charge on the two plates is non-zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] To handle this case, James Clerk Maxwell introduced his *coefficients of potential*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] If three (nearly ideal) conductors are given charges $Q_{1},Q_{2},Q_{3}$ , then the voltage (actually potential) at conductor 1 is given by $V_{1}=P_{11}Q_{1}+P_{12}Q_{2}+P_{13}Q_{3},$ and similarly for the other voltages.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Hermann von Helmholtz and Sir William Thomson showed that the coefficients of potential are symmetric, so that $P_{12}=P_{21}$ , etc.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Similarly, the charge can be written in terms of voltages (actually potentials): $Q_{1}=C_{11}V_{1}+C_{12}V_{2}+C_{13}V_{3},$ The collection of coefficients $C_{ij}={\frac {\partial Q_{i}}{\partial V_{j}}}$ is known as the *capacitance matrix*,.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In open systems which are not charge neutral, so that field lines can end at infinity (which is implicitly assumed to have 0 potential in the above equations), the capacitance and elastance matrices are inverses of each other: $C^{-1}=P$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In closed systems however the capacitance matrix is singular (it has a 0 eigenvalue due to charge neutrality), and so formally the elastance matrix as the inverse of the capacitance matrix is ill defined; it would require independently varying the charges.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Since no actual device holds perfectly equal and opposite charges on each of the two "plates", it is the mutual capacitance that is reported on capacitors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The capacitance of the majority of capacitors used in electronic circuits is generally several orders of magnitude smaller than the farad.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The most common units of capacitance are the microfarad (μF), nanofarad (nF), picofarad (pF), and, in microcircuits, femtofarad (fF).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Some applications also use supercapacitors that can be much larger, as much as hundreds of farads, and parasitic capacitive elements can be less than a femtofarad.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Historical texts use other, obsolete submultiples of the farad, such as "mf" and "mfd" for microfarad (μF); "mmf", "mmfd", "pfd", "μμF" for picofarad (pF).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The capacitance can be calculated if the geometry of the conductors and the dielectric properties of the insulator between the conductors are known.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Capacitance is proportional to the area of overlap and inversely proportional to the separation between conducting sheets.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The closer the sheets are to each other, the greater the capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] An example is the capacitance of a capacitor constructed of two parallel plates both of area ${\textstyle A}$ separated by a distance ${\textstyle d}$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The equation is a good approximation if *d* is small compared to the other dimensions of the plates so that the electric field in the capacitor area is uniform, and the so-called *fringing field* around the periphery provides only a small contribution to the capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Any two adjacent conductors can function as a capacitor, though the capacitance is small unless the conductors are close together for long distances or over a large area.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] This (often unwanted) capacitance is called parasitic or stray capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Stray capacitance can allow signals to leak between otherwise isolated circuits (an effect called crosstalk), and it can be a limiting factor for proper functioning of circuits at high frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Stray capacitance between the input and output in amplifier circuits can be troublesome because it can form a path for feedback, which can cause instability and parasitic oscillation in the amplifier.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] It is often convenient for analytical purposes to replace this capacitance with a combination of one input-to-ground capacitance and one output-to-ground capacitance; the original configuration – including the input-to-output capacitance – is often referred to as a pi-configuration.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Since impedance varies inversely with capacitance, the internode capacitance, *C*, is replaced by a capacitance of KC from input to ground and a capacitance of ⁠(*K* − 1)*C*/*K*⁠ from output to ground.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] When the input-to-output gain is very large, the equivalent input-to-ground impedance is very small while the output-to-ground impedance is essentially equal to the original (input-to-output) impedance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Calculating the capacitance of a system amounts to solving the Laplace equation ${\textstyle \nabla ^{2}\varphi =0}$ with a constant potential ${\textstyle \varphi }$ on the 2-dimensional surface of the conductors embedded in 3-space.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] There is no solution in terms of elementary functions in more complicated cases.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] For plane situations, analytic functions may be used to map different geometries to each other.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The energy (measured in joules) stored in a capacitor is equal to the *work* required to push the charges into the capacitor, i.e. to charge it.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Consider a capacitor of capacitance *C*, holding a charge +*q* on one plate and −*q* on the other.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The energy stored in a capacitor is found by integrating this equation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The capacitance of nanoscale dielectric capacitors such as quantum dots may differ from conventional formulations of larger capacitors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In particular, the electrostatic potential difference experienced by electrons in conventional capacitors is spatially well-defined and fixed by the shape and size of metallic electrodes in addition to the statistically large number of electrons present in conventional capacitors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In nanoscale capacitors, however, the electrostatic potentials experienced by electrons are determined by the number and locations of all electrons that contribute to the electronic properties of the device.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In such devices, the number of electrons may be very small, so the resulting spatial distribution of equipotential surfaces within the device is exceedingly complex.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The capacitance of a connected, or "closed", single-electron device is twice the capacitance of an unconnected, or "open", single-electron device.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] whose energy terms may be obtained as solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] This expression of "quantum capacitance" may be written as $C_{Q}(N)={e^{2} \over U(N)},$ which differs from the conventional expression described in the introduction where $W_{\text{stored}}=U$ , the stored electrostatic potential energy, $C={Q^{2} \over 2U},$ by a factor of ⁠1/2⁠ with $Q=Ne$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] which is appropriate since $\mathrm {d} q=0$ for systems involving either many electrons or metallic electrodes, but in few-electron systems, $\mathrm {d} q\to \Delta \,Q=e$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The integral generally becomes a summation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] One may trivially combine the expressions of capacitance $Q=CV$ and electrostatic interaction energy, $U=QV,$ to obtain $C=Q{1 \over V}=Q{Q \over U}={Q^{2} \over U},$ which is similar to the quantum capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] A more rigorous derivation is reported in the literature.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In particular, to circumvent the mathematical challenges of spatially complex equipotential surfaces within the device, an *average* electrostatic potential experienced by each electron is utilized in the derivation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Apparent mathematical differences may be understood more fundamentally.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The potential energy, $U(N)$ , of an isolated device (self-capacitance) is twice that stored in a "connected" device in the lower limit $N=1$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In nanoscale devices such as quantum dots, the "capacitor" is often an isolated or partially isolated component within the device.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] The primary differences between nanoscale capacitors and macroscopic (conventional) capacitors are the number of excess electrons (charge carriers, or electrons, that contribute to the device's electronic behavior) and the shape and size of metallic electrodes.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In nanoscale devices, nanowires consisting of metal atoms typically do not exhibit the same conductive properties as their macroscopic, or bulk material, counterparts.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In electronic and semiconductor devices, transient or frequency-dependent current between terminals contains both conduction and displacement components.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Conduction current is related to moving charge carriers (electrons, holes, ions, etc.), while displacement current is caused by a time-varying electric field.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Carrier transport is affected by electric fields and by a number of physical phenomena - such as carrier drift and diffusion, trapping, injection, contact-related effects, impact ionization, etc.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] As a result, device admittance is frequency-dependent, and a simple electrostatic formula for capacitance $C=q/V,$ is not applicable.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] A more general definition of capacitance, encompassing electrostatic formula, is: $C={\frac {\operatorname {Im} (Y(\omega ))}{\omega }},$ where $Y(\omega )$ is the device admittance, and $\omega$ is the angular frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] In general, capacitance is a function of frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] At high frequencies, capacitance approaches a constant value, equal to "geometric" capacitance, determined by the terminals' geometry and dielectric content in the device.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] A paper by Steven Laux presents a review of numerical techniques for capacitance calculation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Usually, capacitance in semiconductor devices is positive.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] However, in some devices and under certain conditions (temperature, applied voltages, frequency, etc.), capacitance can become negative.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Non-monotonic behavior of the transient current in response to a step-like excitation has been proposed as the mechanism of negative capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Negative capacitance has been demonstrated and explored in many different types of semiconductor devices.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] A capacitance meter is a piece of electronic test equipment used to measure capacitance, mainly of discrete capacitors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] For most purposes and in most cases the capacitor must be disconnected from circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Many DVMs (digital volt meters) have a capacitance-measuring function.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] These usually operate by charging and discharging the capacitor under test with a known current and measuring the rate of rise of the resulting voltage; the slower the rate of rise, the larger the capacitance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] DVMs can usually measure capacitance from nanofarads to a few hundred microfarads, but wider ranges are not unusual.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] It is also possible to measure capacitance by passing a known high-frequency alternating current through the device under test and measuring the resulting voltage across it (does not work for polarised capacitors).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] More sophisticated instruments use other techniques such as inserting the capacitor-under-test into a bridge circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] By varying the values of the other legs in the bridge (so as to bring the bridge into balance), the value of the unknown capacitor is determined.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] This method of *indirect* use of measuring capacitance ensures greater precision.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/capacitance] Through the use of Kelvin connections and other careful design techniques, these instruments can usually measure capacitors over a range from picofarads to farads.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] To do this, a **controller** with the requisite corrective behavior is required.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This controller monitors the controlled process variable (PV), and compares it with the reference or set point (SP).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The difference between actual and desired value of the process variable, called the *error* signal, or SP-PV error, is applied as feedback to generate a control action to bring the controlled process variable to the same value as the set point.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Other aspects which are also studied are controllability and observability.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Control theory is used in control system engineering to design automation that have revolutionized manufacturing, aircraft, communications and other industries, and created new fields such as robotics.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Extensive use is usually made of a diagrammatic style known as the block diagram.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In it the transfer function, also known as the system function or network function, is a mathematical model of the relation between the input and output based on the differential equations describing the system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Control theory dates from the 19th century, when the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Control theory was further advanced by Edward Routh in 1874, Charles Sturm and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, who all contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria; and from 1922 onwards, the development of PID control theory by Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Although the most direct application of mathematical control theory is its use in control systems engineering (dealing with process control systems for robotics and industry), control theory is routinely applied to problems both the natural and behavioral sciences.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] As the general theory of feedback systems, control theory is useful wherever feedback occurs, making it important to fields like economics, operations research, and the life sciences.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Although control systems of various types date back to antiquity, a more formal analysis of the field began with a dynamics analysis of the centrifugal governor, conducted by the physicist James Clerk Maxwell in 1868, entitled *On Governors*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A centrifugal governor was already used to regulate the velocity of windmills.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Maxwell described and analyzed the phenomenon of self-oscillation, in which lags in the system may lead to overcompensation and unstable behavior.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This generated a flurry of interest in the topic, during which Maxwell's classmate, Edward John Routh, abstracted Maxwell's results for the general class of linear systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Independently, Adolf Hurwitz analyzed system stability using differential equations in 1877, resulting in what is now known as the Routh–Hurwitz theorem.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A notable application of dynamic control was in the area of crewed flight.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The Wright brothers made their first successful test flights on December 17, 1903, and were distinguished by their ability to control their flights for substantial periods (more so than the ability to produce lift from an airfoil, which was known).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Continuous, reliable control of the airplane was necessary for flights lasting longer than a few seconds.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] By World War II, control theory was becoming an important area of research.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control systems, and applied the bang-bang principle to the development of automatic flight control equipment for aircraft.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Other areas of application for discontinuous controls included fire-control systems, guidance systems and electronics.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Sometimes, mechanical methods are used to improve the stability of systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] For example, ship stabilizers are fins mounted beneath the waterline and emerging laterally.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In contemporary vessels, they may be gyroscopically controlled active fins, which have the capacity to change their angle of attack to counteract roll caused by wind or waves acting on the ship.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The Space Race also depended on accurate spacecraft control, and control theory has also seen an increasing use in fields such as economics and artificial intelligence.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Here, one might say that the goal is to find an internal model that obeys the good regulator theorem.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] So, for example, in economics, the more accurately a (stock or commodities) trading model represents the actions of the market, the more easily it can control that market (and extract "useful work" (profits) from it).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] These last two examples take the narrow historical interpretation of control theory as a set of differential equations modeling and regulating kinetic motion, and broaden it into a vast generalization of a regulator interacting with a plant.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A closed-loop controller or feedback controller is a control loop which incorporates feedback, in contrast to an *open-loop controller* or *non-feedback controller*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A closed-loop controller uses feedback to control states or outputs of a dynamical system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In the case of linear feedback systems, a control loop including sensors, control algorithms, and actuators is arranged in an attempt to regulate a variable at a setpoint (SP).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as hills would cause speed changes, and the driver has the ability to alter the desired set speed.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The PID algorithm in the controller restores the actual speed to the desired speed in an optimum way, with minimal delay or overshoot, by controlling the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Control systems that include some sensing of the results they are trying to achieve are making use of feedback and can adapt to varying circumstances to some extent.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Open-loop control systems do not make use of feedback, and run only in pre-arranged ways.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In some systems, closed-loop and open-loop control are used simultaneously.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In such systems, the open-loop control is termed *feedforward* and serves to further improve reference tracking performance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A common closed-loop controller architecture is the PID controller.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In contrast to the frequency-domain analysis of the classical control theory, modern control theory utilizes the time-domain state space representation, a mathematical model of a physical system as a set of input, output and state variables related by first-order differential equations.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] To abstract from the number of inputs, outputs, and states, the variables are expressed as vectors and the differential and algebraic equations are written in matrix form (the latter only being possible when the dynamical system is linear).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The state space representation (also known as the "time-domain approach") provides a convenient and compact way to model and analyze systems with multiple inputs and outputs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] With inputs and outputs, we would otherwise have to write down Laplace transforms to encode all the information about a system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Unlike the frequency domain approach, the use of the state-space representation is not limited to systems with linear components and zero initial conditions.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] "State space" refers to the space whose axes are the state variables.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The state of the system can be represented as a point within that space.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Control systems can be divided into different categories depending on the number of inputs and outputs.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The scope of classical control theory is limited to single-input and single-output (SISO) system design, except when analyzing for disturbance rejection using a second input.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The system analysis is carried out in the time domain using differential equations, in the complex-s domain with the Laplace transform, or in the frequency domain by transforming from the complex-s domain.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Many systems may be assumed to have a second order and single variable system response in the time domain.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A controller designed using classical theory often requires on-site tuning due to incorrect design approximations.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Yet, due to the easier physical implementation of classical controller designs as compared to systems designed using modern control theory, these controllers are preferred in most industrial applications.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The most common controllers designed using classical control theory are PID controllers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A less common implementation may include either or both a Lead or Lag filter.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The ultimate end goal is to meet requirements typically provided in the time-domain called the step response, or at times in the frequency domain called the open-loop response.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The step response characteristics applied in a specification are typically percent overshoot, settling time, etc.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The open-loop response characteristics applied in a specification are typically Gain and Phase margin and bandwidth.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] These characteristics may be evaluated through simulation including a dynamic model of the system under control coupled with the compensation model.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Modern control theory is carried out in the state space, and can deal with multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This overcomes the limitations of classical control theory in more sophisticated design problems, such as fighter aircraft control, with the limitation that no frequency domain analysis is possible.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In modern design, a system is represented to the greatest advantage as a set of decoupled first order differential equations defined using state variables.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Nonlinear, multivariable, adaptive and robust control theories come under this division.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Being fairly new, modern control theory has many areas yet to be explored.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Kálmán and Aleksandr Lyapunov are well known among the people who have shaped modern control theory.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The *stability* of a general dynamical system with no input can be described with Lyapunov stability criteria.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] For simplicity, the following descriptions focus on continuous-time and discrete-time **linear systems**.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Mathematically, this means that for a causal linear system to be stable all of the poles of its transfer function must have negative-real values, i.e. the real part of each pole must be less than zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The difference between the two cases is simply due to the traditional method of plotting continuous time versus discrete time transfer functions.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The continuous Laplace transform is in Cartesian coordinates where the x axis is the real axis and the discrete Z-transform is in circular coordinates where the $\rho$ axis is the real axis.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] When the appropriate conditions above are satisfied a system is said to be asymptotically stable; the variables of an asymptotically stable control system always decrease from their initial value and do not show permanent oscillations.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Permanent oscillations occur when a pole has a real part exactly equal to zero (in the continuous time case) or a modulus equal to one (in the discrete time case).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] If a simply stable system response neither decays nor grows over time, and has no oscillations, it is marginally stable; in this case the system transfer function has non-repeated poles at the complex plane origin (i.e. their real and complex component is zero in the continuous time case).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Oscillations are present when poles with real part equal to zero have an imaginary part not equal to zero.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] which has a pole in $z=0.5$ (zero imaginary part).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This system is BIBO (asymptotically) stable since the pole is *inside* the unit circle.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] which has a pole at $z=1.5$ and is not BIBO stable since the pole has a modulus strictly greater than one.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Numerous tools exist for the analysis of the poles of a system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] These include graphical systems like the root locus, Bode plots or the Nyquist plots.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Mechanical changes can make equipment (and control systems) more stable.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Sailors add ballast to improve the stability of ships.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Cruise ships use antiroll fins that extend transversely from the side of the ship for perhaps 30 feet (10 m) and are continuously rotated about their axes to develop forces that oppose the roll.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Controllability and observability are main issues in the analysis of a system before deciding the best control strategy to be applied, or whether it is even possible to control or stabilize the system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Controllability is related to the possibility of forcing the system into a particular state by using an appropriate control signal.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, then no signal will ever be able to control the state.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, but its dynamics are stable, then the state is termed *stabilizable*.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Observability instead is related to the possibility of *observing*, through output measurements, the state of a system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] If a state is not observable, the controller will never be able to determine the behavior of an unobservable state and hence cannot use it to stabilize the system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] However, similar to the stabilizability condition above, if a state cannot be observed it might still be detectable.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] From a geometrical point of view, looking at the states of each variable of the system to be controlled, every "bad" state of these variables must be controllable and observable to ensure a good behavior in the closed-loop system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] That is, if one of the eigenvalues of the system is not both controllable and observable, this part of the dynamics will remain untouched in the closed-loop system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] If such an eigenvalue is not stable, the dynamics of this eigenvalue will be present in the closed-loop system which therefore will be unstable.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Unobservable poles are not present in the transfer function realization of a state-space representation, which is why sometimes the latter is preferred in dynamical systems analysis.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Solutions to problems of an uncontrollable or unobservable system include adding actuators and sensors.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Several different control strategies have been devised in the past years.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] These vary from extremely general ones (PID controller), to others devoted to very particular classes of systems (especially robotics or aircraft cruise control).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A control problem can have several specifications.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Stability, of course, is always present.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The controller must ensure that the closed-loop system is stable, regardless of the open-loop stability.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A poor choice of controller can even worsen the stability of the open-loop system, which must normally be avoided.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Sometimes it would be desired to obtain particular dynamics in the closed loop: i.e. that the poles have $Re[\lambda ]<-{\overline {\lambda }}$ , where ${\overline {\lambda }}$ is a fixed value strictly greater than zero, instead of simply asking that $Re[\lambda ]<0$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Another typical specification is the rejection of a step disturbance; including an integrator in the open-loop chain (i.e. directly before the system under control) easily achieves this.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Other classes of disturbances need different types of sub-systems to be included.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Other "classical" control theory specifications regard the time-response of the closed-loop system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] These include the rise time (the time needed by the control system to reach the desired value after a perturbation), peak overshoot (the highest value reached by the response before reaching the desired value) and others (settling time, quarter-decay).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Frequency domain specifications are usually related to robustness (see after).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Modern performance assessments use some variation of integrated tracking error (IAE, ISA, CQI).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A control system must always have some robustness property.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A robust controller is such that its properties do not change much if applied to a system slightly different from the mathematical one used for its synthesis.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This requirement is important, as no real physical system truly behaves like the series of differential equations used to represent it mathematically.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Typically a simpler mathematical model is chosen in order to simplify calculations, otherwise, the true system dynamics can be so complicated that a complete model is impossible.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The process of determining the equations that govern the model's dynamics is called system identification.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This can be done off-line: for example, executing a series of measures from which to calculate an approximated mathematical model, typically its transfer function or matrix.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Such identification from the output, however, cannot take account of unobservable dynamics.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Sometimes the model is built directly starting from known physical equations, for example, in the case of a mass-spring-damper system we know that $m{\ddot {x}}(t)=-Kx(t)-\mathrm {B} {\dot {x}}(t)$ .
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Some advanced control techniques include an "on-line" identification process (see later).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The parameters of the model are calculated ("identified") while the controller itself is running.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In this way, if a drastic variation of the parameters ensues, for example, if the robot's arm releases a weight, the controller will adjust itself consequently in order to ensure the correct performance.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Analysis of the robustness of a SISO (single input single output) control system can be performed in the frequency domain, considering the system's transfer function and using Nyquist and Bode diagrams.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Topics include gain and phase margin and amplitude margin.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] For MIMO (multi-input multi output) and, in general, more complicated control systems, one must consider the theoretical results devised for each control technique (see next section).
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] I.e., if particular robustness qualities are needed, the engineer must shift their attention to a control technique by including these qualities in its properties.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A particular robustness issue is the requirement for a control system to perform properly in the presence of input and state constraints.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In the physical world every signal is limited.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] It could happen that a controller will send control signals that cannot be followed by the physical system, for example, trying to rotate a valve at excessive speed.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] This can produce undesired behavior of the closed-loop system, or even damage or break actuators or other subsystems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Specific control techniques are available to solve the problem: model predictive control (see later), and anti-wind up systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The latter consists of an additional control block that ensures that the control signal never exceeds a given threshold.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] For MIMO systems, pole placement can be performed mathematically using a state space representation of the open-loop system and calculating a feedback matrix assigning poles in the desired positions.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In complicated systems this can require computer-assisted calculation capabilities, and cannot always ensure robustness.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Furthermore, all system states are not in general measured and so observers must be included and incorporated in pole placement design.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Processes in industries like robotics and the aerospace industry typically have strong nonlinear dynamics.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] In control theory it is sometimes possible to linearize such classes of systems and apply linear techniques, but in many cases it can be necessary to devise from scratch theories permitting control of nonlinear systems.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] These, e.g., feedback linearization, backstepping, sliding mode control, trajectory linearization control normally take advantage of results based on Lyapunov's theory.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Differential geometry has been widely used as a tool for generalizing well-known linear control concepts to the nonlinear case, as well as showing the subtleties that make it a more challenging problem.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Control theory has also been used to decipher the neural mechanism that directs cognitive states.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] When the system is controlled by multiple controllers, the problem is one of decentralized control.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Decentralization is helpful in many ways, for instance, it helps control systems to operate over a larger geographical area.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The agents in decentralized control systems can interact using communication channels and coordinate their actions.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A stochastic control problem is one in which the evolution of the state variables is subjected to random shocks from outside the system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] A deterministic control problem is not subject to external random shocks.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Every control system must guarantee first the stability of the closed-loop behavior.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] For linear systems, this can be obtained by directly placing the poles.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] Nonlinear control systems use specific theories (normally based on Aleksandr Lyapunov's Theory) to ensure stability without regard to the inner dynamics of the system.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/control-theory] The possibility to fulfill different specifications varies from the model considered and the control strategy chosen.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Parasitic oscillation is undesirable for several reasons.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] The oscillations may be coupled into other circuits or radiate as radio waves, causing electromagnetic interference (EMI) to other devices.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] In audio systems, parasitic oscillations can sometimes be heard as annoying sounds in the speakers or earphones.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] The oscillations waste power and may cause undesirable heating.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] For example, an audio power amplifier that goes into parasitic oscillation may generate enough power to damage connected speakers.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] A circuit that is oscillating will not amplify linearly, so desired signals passing through the stage will be distorted.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] In digital circuits, parasitic oscillations may only occur on particular logic transitions and may result in erratic operation of subsequent stages; for example, a counter stage may see many spurious pulses and count erratically.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Parasitic oscillation in an amplifier stage occurs when part of the output energy is coupled into the input, with the correct phase and amplitude to provide positive feedback at some frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] The coupling can occur directly between input and output wiring with stray capacitance or mutual inductance between input and output.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] In some solid-state or vacuum electron devices there is sufficient internal capacitance to provide a feedback path.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Since the ground is common to both input and output, output current flowing through the impedance of the ground connection can also couple signals back to the input.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Similarly, impedance in the power supply can couple input to output and cause oscillation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] When a common power supply is used for several stages of amplification, the supply voltage may vary with the changing current in the output stage.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] The power supply voltage changes will appear in the input stage as positive feedback.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] An example is a transistor radio which plays well with a fresh battery, but squeals or "motorboats" when the battery is old.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] In audio systems, if a microphone is placed close to a loudspeaker, parasitic oscillations may occur.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] This is caused by positive feedback, from amplifier's output to loudspeaker to sound waves, and back via the microphone to the amplifier input.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Feedback control theory was developed to address the problem of parasitic oscillation in servo control systems – the systems oscillated rather than performing their intended function, for example velocity control in engines.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] In practice, feedback may occur over a range of frequencies (for example the operating range of an amplifier); at various frequencies, the phase of the amplifier may be different.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] If there is one frequency where the feedback is positive and the amplitude condition is also fulfilled – the system will oscillate at that frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] These conditions can be expressed in mathematical terms using the Nyquist plot.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Another method used in control loop theory uses Bode plots of gain and phase vs. frequency.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Using Bode plots, a design engineer checks whether there is a frequency where both conditions for oscillations are met: the phase is zero (positive feedback) and the loop gain is 1 or greater.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] When parasitic oscillations occur, the designer can use the various tools of control loop engineering to correct the situation – to reduce the gain or to change the phase at problematic frequencies.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Several measures are used to prevent parasitic oscillation.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Amplifier circuits are laid out so that input and output wiring are not adjacent, preventing capacitive or inductive coupling.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] A metal shield may be placed over sensitive portions of the circuit.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Bypass capacitors may be put at power supply connections, to provide a low-impedance path for AC signals and prevent interstage coupling through the power supply.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] Where printed circuit boards are used, high- and low-power stages are separated and ground return traces are arranged so that heavy currents don't flow in mutually shared portions of the ground trace.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] In some cases the problem may only be solved by introduction of another feedback *neutralization* network, calculated and adjusted to eliminate the negative feedback within the passband of the amplifying device.
[src:parasitic-oscillation/parasitic-oscillation] A classic example is the Neutrodyne circuit used in tuned radio frequency receivers.
